# Caching Strategy

Coding patterns for caching at every layer - browser, application, API, database, CDN. IF your project needs caching, apply these patterns.

> All numeric values (thresholds, sizes, timings, percentages) in this file are `[DEFAULT]` - adjust per project.

---

## Audience test (HTTP / API)

| Data | Cache |
|------|--------|
| Same for all users (catalog, public config) | `public` + short TTL or framework cache where safe |
| User-specific (cart, account, permissions) | `private` / `no-store` - never shared-cache |
| Auth/session/token responses | **`no-store`** always |
| Mutations | **`no-store`** |

When in doubt, prefer freshness over aggressive cache.

---

## Caching Layers

```
User ──> Browser Cache ──> CDN / Edge ──> API Server ──> App Cache ──> Database Cache ──> Database
                                                         (Redis/memory)   (query cache)

Each layer catches requests before they hit the next, reducing load and latency.
```

---

## Browser Cache

### Static Assets (CSS, JS, Images, Fonts)

```
Strategy: Cache forever, bust on change

Headers:
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
  (= cache for 1 year, never revalidate)

Cache busting:
  style.abc123.css     <- hash in filename changes when content changes
  app.def456.js        <- build tool generates unique hash per build

Rule: Static assets should have content-hash in filename + long max-age for optimal caching. Legacy stacks and dynamically injected scripts may need different strategies.
```

### API Responses

```
Strategy: Short-lived or no-cache for dynamic data

Public data (same for all users):
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=60, stale-while-revalidate=300
  (= cache 1 minute, serve stale for 5 more minutes while refreshing)

Private data (user-specific):
  Cache-Control: private, no-cache
  (= don't cache in shared caches, always revalidate with server)

Mutations (POST, PUT, DELETE):
  Cache-Control: no-store
  (= never cache)
```

### Rules

- **Static assets**: Long cache + content hash = always fast, always fresh
- **API data**: Short or no cache - stale data is worse than slow data for most apps
- **Auth-related responses**: NEVER cache (`no-store`) - token, session, permissions
- **ETag / Last-Modified**: Use for conditional requests (304 Not Modified saves bandwidth)
- **Vary header**: Include `Vary: Authorization` if response differs per user

