## Framework Data Cache (RSC / Next.js / Server Components)

IF your framework has a built-in server data cache (Next.js `unstable_cache` / `fetch` cache + `revalidateTag`, Remix loaders, Nuxt `useAsyncData`, etc.), treat it as **two tiers** and use tags for invalidation. Pattern (Next.js shown - adapt to your framework):

```
Tier 1 - Per-request memoization (dedupe within ONE request/render)
  -> React `cache()` / request-scoped memo
  -> Same query called by 3 components in one render -> 1 DB hit
  -> Lives for the request only; never serves stale data across requests

Tier 2 - Cross-request data cache (shared across users/requests)
  -> unstable_cache(fn, keyParts, { tags: ["catalog"], revalidate })
  -> Survives between requests; keyed + tagged
  -> Public, same-for-all-users data only - NEVER user-scoped data
```

### Rules

- **Wrap public read queries in BOTH tiers** - request memo (Tier 1) inside the cached function, persistent cache (Tier 2) around it - so one render dedupes and repeat renders skip the DB.
- **Tag every cached read by domain** (`catalog`, `product:{id}`, `offers`) so writes can purge precisely with `revalidateTag(tag)`.
- **NEVER put user-scoped data in Tier 2** - cart, account, orders, permissions, session. Tier 2 is shared across requests; a per-user value would leak to other users. Use Tier 1 (request memo) only for those.
- **Writes invalidate tags after commit** - admin/staff mutation that changes cached public data calls `revalidateTag(...)` after a successful write (mirror of `api-design.md` § Cache Headers & Invalidation). Never rely on `revalidate` TTL alone for admin edits.
- **ISR / page revalidation** - public pages built from cached data use time-based `revalidate` as a safety net AND on-demand `revalidateTag`/`revalidatePath` on write for freshness. Pick the longest TTL the page can tolerate; rely on tag busting for immediacy.
- **Boot warm (optional)** - for a small set of always-needed hot reads (home catalog, active offers, feature flags), warm the cache once on server boot so the first user does not pay the cold-cache cost. Keep the warm set tiny; everything else fills lazily.

